# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aiohttp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aiohttp/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:aiohttp/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:aiohttp/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:aiohttp/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] The **Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface** (**ASGI**) is a calling convention for web servers to forward requests to asynchronous-capable Python frameworks, and applications.
[src:aiohttp/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] It is built as a successor to the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI).
[src:aiohttp/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] Where WSGI provided a standard for synchronous Python applications, ASGI provides one for both asynchronous and synchronous applications, with a WSGI backwards-compatibility implementation and multiple servers and application frameworks.
[src:aiohttp/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] ASGI is also designed to be a superset of WSGI, and there's a defined way of translating between the two, allowing WSGI applications to be run inside ASGI servers through a translation wrapper (provided in the asgiref library).
[src:aiohttp/asynchronous-server-gateway-interface] A threadpool can be used to run the synchronous WSGI applications away from the async event loop.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:aiohttp/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:aiohttp/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] In order to implement a web server, first create a request handler.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Now, head over to `http://localhost:8080/` to see the results.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Both ways essentially do the same work, the difference is only in your taste: do you prefer *Django style* with famous `urls.py` or *Flask* with shiny route decorators.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Graceful shutdown section explains what `run_app()` does and how to implement complex server initialization/finalization from scratch.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Application runners for more handling more complex cases like *asynchronous* web application serving and multiple hosts support.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] For local development we typically recommend using aiohttp-devtools.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] A request handler must be a coroutine that accepts a `Request` instance as its only argument and returns a `StreamResponse` derived (e.g.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The *HTTP method* can be queried later in the request handler using the `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.method` property.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] By default endpoints added with `GET` method will accept `HEAD` requests and return the same response headers as they would for a `GET` request.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Here `handler` won’t be called on `HEAD` request and the server will respond with `405: Method Not Allowed`.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Peer disconnection section explains how handlers behave when a client connection drops and ways to optimize handling of this.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Internally routes are served by `Application.router` (`UrlDispatcher` instance).
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Resource is an entry in *route table* which corresponds to requested URL.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Resource in turn has at least one *route*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Route corresponds to handling *HTTP method* by calling *web handler*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Thus when you add a *route* the *resource* object is created under the hood.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The library implementation **merges** all subsequent route additions for the same path adding the only resource for all HTTP methods.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] For instance, a resource with the path `'/a/{name}/c'` would match all incoming requests with paths such as `'/a/b/c'`, `'/a/1/c'`, and `'/a/etc/c'`.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] A variable *part* is specified in the form `{identifier}`, where the `identifier` can be used later in a request handler to access the matched value for that *part*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] By default, each *part* matches the regular expression `[^{}/]+`.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] But sometimes it’s convenient to group logically similar handlers into a Python *class*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` has support for *class based views*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Handlers should be coroutines accepting *self* only and returning response object as regular web-handler.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Request object can be retrieved by `View.request` property.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Example will process GET and POST requests for */path/to* but raise *405 Method not allowed* exception for unimplemented HTTP methods.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Code examples shown above use *imperative* style for adding new routes: they call `app.router.add_get(...)` etc.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] There are two alternatives: route tables and route decorators.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The snippet calls `add_routes()` to register a list of *route definitions* (`aiohttp.web.RouteDef` instances) created by `aiohttp.web.get()` or `aiohttp.web.post()` functions.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The example creates a `aiohttp.web.RouteTableDef` container first.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The container is a list-like object with additional decorators `aiohttp.web.RouteTableDef.get()`, `aiohttp.web.RouteTableDef.post()` etc. for registering new routes.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] After filling the container `add_routes()` is used for adding registered *route definitions* into application’s router.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] All tree ways (imperative calls, route tables and decorators) are equivalent, you could use what do you prefer or even mix them on your own.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The shortcut method returns `aiohttp.web.Response` instance so you can for example set cookies before returning it from handler.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Often you need a container for storing user data across requests.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The concept is usually called a *session*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] HTTP Forms are supported out of the box.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] If form’s method is `"GET"` (`<form method="get">`) use `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.query` for getting form data.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] To access form data with `"POST"` method use `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.post()` or `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.multipart()`.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.post()` accepts both `'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'` and `'multipart/form-data'` form’s data encoding (e.g.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] `<form enctype="multipart/form-data">`).
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] It stores files data in temporary directory.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] If *client_max_size* is specified *post* raises *ValueError* exception.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] For efficiency use `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.multipart()`, It is especially effective for uploading large files (File Uploads).
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` has built-in support for handling files uploaded from the browser.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] First, make sure that the HTML `<form>` element has its *enctype* attribute set to `enctype="multipart/form-data"`.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Then, in the request handler you can access the file input field as a `FileField` instance.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] You might have noticed a big warning in the example above.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] The general issue is that `aiohttp.web.BaseRequest.post()` reads the whole payload in memory, resulting in possible OOM errors.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` supports *WebSockets* out-of-the-box.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] `aiohttp.web` defines a set of exceptions for every *HTTP status code*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Returning `HTTPException` or its subclasses is deprecated and will be removed in subsequent aiohttp versions.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] Each exception class has a status code according to **RFC 2068**: codes with 100-300 are not really errors; 400s are client errors, and 500s are server errors.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] If not directly specified, *headers* will be added to the *default response headers*.
[src:aiohttp/web-quickstart] where *location* is value for *Location HTTP header*.
